user_message:
An agent A claimed that the following OS_ModuleLoad_Impl code violates the MISRA C 2023 rule 21.17.
<misra_rule>
MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17 is Use of the string handling functions from <string.h> shall not result in accesses beyond the bounds of the objects referenced by their pointer parameters.
This rule strictly applies to the Standard Library functions in <string.h> such as memcpy, memmove, memset, memcmp, strcpy, strncpy, strcat, strncat, strlen, and strspn.
</misra_rule>
<target_code>
Here is the original code of OS_ModuleLoad_Impl.
```c
int32 OS_ModuleLoad_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token, const char *translated_path)
{
    int32                             status = OS_ERROR;
    int                               dl_mode;
    OS_impl_module_internal_record_t *impl;
    OS_module_internal_record_t *     module;

    impl   = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_module_table, *token);
    module = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_module_table, *token);

    /*
     * RTLD_NOW should instruct dlopen() to resolve all the symbols in the
     * module immediately, as opposed to waiting until they are used.
     * The latter (lazy mode) is non-deterministic - a resolution error on
     * a rarely-used symbol could cause a random failure far in the future.
     */
    dl_mode = RTLD_NOW;

    if ((module->flags & OS_MODULE_FLAG_LOCAL_SYMBOLS) != 0)
    {
        /*
         * Do not add the symbols in this module to the global symbol table.
         * This mode helps prevent any unanticipated references into this
         * module, which can in turn prevent unloading via dlclose().
         */
        dl_mode |= RTLD_LOCAL;
    }
    else
    {
        /*
         * Default mode - add symbols to the global symbol table, so they
         * will be available to resolve symbols in future module loads.
         * However, any such references will prevent unloading of this
         * module via dlclose().
         */
        dl_mode |= RTLD_GLOBAL;
    }

    dlerror();
    impl->dl_handle = dlopen(translated_path, dl_mode);
    if (impl->dl_handle != NULL)
    {
        status = OS_SUCCESS;
    }
    else
    {
        OS_DEBUG("Error loading shared library: %s\n", dlerror());
    }

    return status;
}
```
</target_code>
<response format>
Provide your answer with these fields.
- explanation: your evaluation of the scenario provided by the agent A.
- is_report_correct: whether the report is correct or not (true/false). True means there is a violation.
</response format>
<scenario>
The agent A provided the following violation scenario:
memchr(name_ptr, 0, OS_MAX_FILE_NAME) can read up to OS_MAX_FILE_NAME bytes starting at name_ptr, but the function only guarantees VirtualPath is null-terminated within OS_MAX_PATH_LEN bytes (VirtPathLen < OS_MAX_PATH_LEN). There is no guarantee that at least OS_MAX_FILE_NAME bytes are accessible from name_ptr. If the remaining bytes from name_ptr to the end of the actual object (e.g. a buffer allocated exactly for the filename) are less than OS_MAX_FILE_NAME, memchr will read past the object bounds (undefined behavior). Example: VirtualPath is a small dynamically sized buffer holding ".../name" where the chars after the terminating '\0' are not part of the object; if OS_MAX_FILE_NAME is larger than the name length, memchr may access out-of-bounds memory. This violates MISRA C 2023 Rule 21.17.
</scenario>
